==English==

===Alternative forms===
* {{l|en|underly}}

===Etymology===
From {{inh|en|enm|underlien}}, {{m|enm|underliggen}}, from {{inh|en|ang|underliċġan|t=to underlie, to be subject to, give way to}}, equivalent to {{prefix|en|under|lie}}. Cognate with {{cog|nl|onderliggen|t=to lie below, lie on the bottom of}}, {{cog|de|unterliegen|t=to lie under, be subject to, succumb}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/ˌʌn.də(ɹ)ˈlaɪ/|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|aɪ|lang=en}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb|underlies|underlying|underlay|underlain}}

# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To lie in a [[position]] directly beneath.
#: ''A stratum of clay '''underlies''' the surface gravel.''
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To lie under or beneath.
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[serve]] as a [[basis]] of; form the [[foundation]] of.
#: ''a doctrine '''underlying''' a theory''
#* '''1941''', {{w|Emily Carr}}, ''{{w|Klee Wyck}}'', Chapter 6,<sup>[http://www.gutenberg.net.au/ebooks01/0100131.txt]</sup>
#*: {{...}} she was carved into the bole of a red cedar tree. Sun and storm had bleached the wood, moss here and there softened the crudeness of the modelling; sincerity '''underlay''' every stroke.
#* {{quote-magazine|year=2013|month=July-August|author=[http://www.americanscientist.org/authors/detail/sarah-glaz Sarah Glaz]
|title=[http://www.americanscientist.org/issues/pub/2013/4/ode-to-prime-numbers Ode to Prime Numbers]
|volume=101|issue=4|magazine={{w|American Scientist}}
|passage=Some poems, echoing the purpose of early poetic treatises on scientific principles, attempt to elucidate the mathematical concepts that '''underlie''' prime numbers. Others play with primes’ cultural associations. Still others derive their structure from mathematical patterns involving primes.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To be [[subject]] to; be [[liable]] to answer, as a charge or challenge.
#* Sir Walter Scott
#*: The knight of Ivanhoe {{...}} '''underlies''' the challenge of Brian der Bois Guilbert.
# {{lb|en|mining}} To [[underlay]].

